This film does something incredible. It's easy to see how juvenile the characters are and get impatient with them throughout the first half. But by the end, as they are grappling with their own limitations, I start seeing so much of myself in them. I probably watched this at the perfect time in my life.
This was a banger. The power of cinema…

Review: The story has a great premise, but has nothing meaningful to say about the topic of cancel culture, so the later acts stall.

Perfectly crafted to the genre, just fantastic work to stay true to all the genre tropes and cliches that make noirs so satisfying. The wonderfully realized plot and characters manage to create something new in spite of these cliches. A stylish, smart movie only held back by the terrible romance it tries to pull off.
This is just the most charming thing, absolutely loved it.
The satire scenes were great! The film could have been higher percentage satire.

A beautiful depiction of solidarity. The sauna is a refuge for these women to get away from a society that tries to define womanhood as something much too narrow for them to freely be their full, unhindered selves. Their resilience in spite of this pain is displayed so beautifully here.

A meditation on the purpose of life, contrasting the views of appreciating a humble, modest existence versus experimenting with the extremes of human experience to find out who you are.The minimal visual language here can make you wonder if this needed to be a movie at all. The writing is truly wonderful, though you can’t help but have your mind wander, especially since the film is asking you to relate the conversation to your own life, but then quickly…
Legendary comedic writing! Marilyn Monroe is insanely good.
Such a charming duo. A proto-Ethan Hawke and the best child actress you will ever see just killing it with their performances. Masterful character writing.
